  <mads:note type="source">Wikipedia: "Ekkehard I (died 14 January 973), called Major (the Elder),
        was a monk of the Abbey of Saint Gall. He was of noble birth, of the Jonschwyl family in
        Toggenburg, and was educated in the monastery of St. Gall; after joining the Benedictine
        Order, he was appointed director of the inner school there. ...... He was also distinguished
        as a poet, and wrote a Latin epic "Waltharius", basing his version on an original German
        text. He dedicated this poem to Bishop Erkanbald of Strasburg (965-991). It describes the
        elopement of Walter of Aquitaine with the Burgundian princess Hildegunde, from the land of
        the Huns, followed by the battle of Wasgenstein between Walter and the followers of Gunther
        and Hagen (ed. Peiper, Berlin, 1873)...</mads:note>
